  "text": "A controlled ovarian stimulation model developed for the collection of multiple oocytes for in vitro fertilization [CITATION_1] was used to obtain granulosa cells and follicular fluid (n ϭ 4-5/time point). Beginning within 3 days of initiation of menstruation, monkeys received 60 IU of recombinant human (r-h) FSH (also known as FSHB; Serono Reproductive Biology Institute, Rockland, MA; Days 1-6, i.m.), followed by 60 IU of r-hFSH plus 30 IU r-hLH (also known as LHB; Serono; Days 7-8, i.m.) to stimulate the growth of multiple follicles. Animals also received the GnRH antagonist Antide (Serono; 0.5 mg/kg body weight, s.c.) daily to prevent an endogenous ovulatory LH surge. Follicular development was monitored by serum estradiol levels and by ultrasonography [CITATION_2] . Follicular aspiration was performed before (0 h) and 12, 24, or 36 h after administration of 1000 IU r-hCG (also known as CGB5; Serono; Day 9, i.m.).",
